properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For Rivers And Creeks In Southeastern Manitoba.
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the rivers and creeks in southeastern Manitoba due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system in Alberta will pass through central Saskatchewan tonight and then into Manitoba Saturday. A cold front trailing from this low will push through southwestern Saskatchewan tonight bringing very gusty northwest winds. For most areas gusts of 70 or 80 km/h should be expected tonight. Some localities are likely to receive wind gusts of 90 or 100 km/h this evening as the cold front passes through. Gusty northwest winds will spread throughout southern Saskatchewan by Saturday morning as the cold front sweeps through, although they are not expected to reach warning criteria. This weather system will bring above normal temperatures today, but much colder temperatures Saturday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A significant rainfall is possible Saturday night into Sunday morning. A low pressure system will approach Southern Ontario late Saturday, with rain developing over the area Saturday evening. Rain, heavy at times, will continue through Saturday night into Sunday morning. Total rainfall amounts of 30 to 50 mm are possible, with the heaviest rain falling overnight Saturday. Gusty easterly winds up to 60 km/h are possible. Rain will taper to scattered showers Sunday evening. Rainfall warnings are not expected to be issued with this event. Ensure that storm drains are clear of leaves and other debris. Heavy downpours can cause flash floods as well as water pooling on roads. Local power outages are possible. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-26T11:02:51-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-25T19:03:51-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3392206220.2019

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A cold front sweeping south through Alberta will continue to bring some snowfall to the western parts of the province. Areas of higher terrain are especially at risk this evening. Conditions are expected to improve gradually as the low pressure centre moves into Saskatchewan. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A cold front that swept through Alberta Friday afternoon is now moving into southwestern Saskatchewan as of early this evening. Numerous reports of winds gusting in excess of 100 km/h were reported as the front crossed Alberta, and very gusty northwest winds are expected tonight in the wake of this feature as it moves through Saskatchewan. The wind is not expected to be quite as strong as the cold front moves through the province, but many areas in southern Saskatchewan will still see gusts of 80 to 100 km/h tonight. Much colder temperatures are expected Saturday in the wake of the cold front. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A cold front sweeping south through Alberta will continue to bring some snowfall to the western parts of the province. Areas of higher terrain are especially at risk this evening. Conditions are expected to improve gradually as the low pressure centre moves into Saskatchewan. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
